A Hadamard matrix of order $n$ is an real $n\times n$ matrix $H$ which
satisfies the identity
\begin{gather*}
  HH^{T}= nI
\end{gather*}
An equivalent definition for Hadamard matrices is a square matrix
whose elements come from the set $\{1, -1\}$ and whose rows are all
orthogonal.  These matrices were invented by James Joseph Sylvester in
1867, who called them anallagmatic pavements.  Sylvester also
developed a construction for this type of matrix, which will be shown
later.  Hadamard matrices are often visualized using colored blocks,
where the black blocks represent the ones in the matrix and the white
blocks represent negative ones.  Figure 1 shows an example of a
Hadamard matrix of order 16.
