Changing the sign of all entries of a row or column of a Hadamard
matrix will result in another Hadamard matrix.  Similarly, permuting
rows and columns of a Hadamard matrix or transposing the matrix will
result in a Hadamard matrix.  Any Hadamard matrix found through such a
series of transformations considered equivalent to the original
matrix.  Often, Hadamard matrices are normalized, meaning the first
row andcolumn are made to be entirely of
ones\cite{hallm}. This is usually achieved through a
series of sign changes of rows and columns; thus, the normalized
matrix is equivalent to the original.

Whether a Hadamard matrix of a given order exists is, in many cases,
an unsolved problem.  The following theorem, however, gives a
necessary condition for their existence.
\begin{theorem}
  If a Hadamard matrix of order $n$ exists, then $n=1,2$  or
  $n\equiv0\pmod{4}$.
  \begin{proof}
    The following is a proof of this theorem taken from Combinatorial
    Theory by Hall\cite{hallm}.  A Hadamard matrix of order
    $1$ is $(1)$.  For order two, there exists the Hadamard matrix $
    \begin{pmatrix}
      1 & 1\\
      1 & -1
    \end{pmatrix}$.  For $n\geq3$, suppose the matrix has been
    normalized so that entire first row is made of ones.  There exist
    four possible combinations of ones and negative ones for the next
    two entries in each column: $(+1,+1)$, $(+1,-1)$, $(-1,+1)$ and
    $(-1,-1)$.  Therefore, arranget he columns so that all columns
    starting with  $(+1,+1,+1)$ are together and those starting with
    $(+1,+1,-1)$  are together and soforth for all four types of
    columns.  The matrix would be in the following form:
    \begin{gather*}
      \begin{pmatrix}
        + & \dots & + & + & \dots & + & + & \dots & + & + & \dots & +\\
        + & \dots & + & + & \dots & + & - & \dots & - & - & \dots & -\\
        + & \dots & + & - & \dots & - & + & \dots & + & - & \dots & -\\
      \end{pmatrix}
    \end{gather*}
    Let $a$ be the number of columns of the first type and let $b$,
    $c$ and $d$ be the numbers of columns of the second third and
    fourth types, respectively.  Then the following equation can be
    written:
    \begin{align*}
      a+b &= c+d= \sfrac{n}{2}\\
      a+c &= b+d= \sfrac{n}{2}\\
      a+d &= b+d= \sfrac{n}{2}\\
    \end{align*}
    Solving this system of equationsleads to $a = b = c = d =
    \sfrac{n}{4}$. Thus, since $a$, $b$, $c$ and $d$ are integers, $n$
    must be amultiple of four.\cite{hallm}
  \end{proof}
\end{theorem}
Although Sylvester invented matrices of this type, it was actually
Jacques Hadamard for whom these matrices are named.  This is a result
ofthe following theorem by Hadamard.

\begin{theorem}
  Let $X= (x_{ij})$ be a real $n\times n$ matrix whose entries
  satisfy $\abs{a_{ij}}\leq1$ for all $i$ and $j$. Then,
  $\abs{\det{X}}\leq n^{\sfrac{n}{2}}$. Equality holds if and only if
  $X$ is a Hadamard matrix.\cite{cameron1}
  \begin{proof}
    This theorem can be proven using a geometric interpretation of the
    determinant. The following proof is taken from Combinatorics:
    Topics, Techniques, Algorithms by Cameron.\cite{cameron1}
    Viewed geometrically, the determinant of a matrix $X$ is the
    volume of a parallelpiped in the $n$-dimensional Euclidian space
    whose sides are represented by the rows of $X$. Since it was
    assumed that all entries of the matrix were less than or equal to
    one, then the maximum possible Euclidian length of any side is
    $\sqrt{n}$.  The maximum possible volume of the parallelpiped is
    the product of the edge lengths.  The volume is equal to the
    maximum possible volume if and only if the edges are all
    perpendicular to one another.  Thus, the maximum possible volume
    for the parallelpiped, and, in turn, the maximum possible
    determinant of X, is $n^{\sfrac{n}{2}}$.  This maximum value is
    reached only if the length of all sides are $\sqrt{n}$ and the
    sides are mutually perpendicular.  In the matrix $X$, this would
    correspond to all entries being either $\pm1$ and each row of the
    matrix being orthogonal to allothers.  This is equivalent to
    $XX^{T}=nI$.\cite{cameron1}
  \end{proof}
\end{theorem}

Once Hadamard had proven this theorem, he conjectured that a Hadamard
matrix of order $n$ exists for $n=1,2$ or $n\equiv0\pmod{4}$. This
conjecture is one of the great unsolved problems in mathematics today.
Although it remains unproven, those attempting to prove it have made
many advances in the field of Combinatorics.  Also, there has been
some progress in proving the existence of Hadamard matrices of
specific orders through various constructions and computer
searches. Most recently, in 2004, Hadi Kharaghani and Behruz
Tayfeh-Rezaie found a Hadamard matrix of order
428.\cite{kharaghani} Currently, the smallest factor of four
for which there exists no known Hadamard matrix is 668.

\section{Constructions of Hadamard Matrices}
\label{sec:const}

As mentioned previously, many Hadamard matrices can be formed using
various constructions.  Some of the earliest and most famous
constructions are those by Sylvester, Paley and Williamson, but others
do exist.  The first construction of Hadamard matrices was found by
their inventor, James Joseph Sylvester, in 1867.  He used the
Kronecker product ortens or product to find new Hadamard matrices from
old ones.\cite{cameron2} By this construction, he was able
to show that a Hadamard matrix exists for all .

In general, if $A=(a_{ij})$ is an $m\times n$ matrix and $B= (b_{kl})$
is an $p\times q$ matrix, then their Kronecker product $A\otimes B$ is
the $mp\times nq$ matrix made up of $p\times q$ blocks where the
$(i,j)$ block is $a_{ij}B$.  Then the result for Hadamard matrices is
as follows:
\begin{theorem}
  The Kronecker product of a Hadamard matrix is a Hadamard matrix.
  \begin{proof}
    The subsequent proof is from Combinatorics: Topics, Techniques,
    Algorithms by Cameron\cite{cameron1}. The following
    properties of Kronecker products will be utilized in the proof:
    $(A\otimes B) (B\otimes C)= AC\otimes CD$ and $(A\otimes B)^{T}=
    A^{T} \otimes B^{T}$. 

    Suppose there exist two Hadamard matrices, $H_{1}$, which is of
    order $n_{1}$, and $H_{2}$, which is of order $n_{2}$. Then taking
    the Kronecker product of these, we get $H_{1}\otimes H_{2}$, which
    is of size $n_{1}n_{2}$.  In order to be a Hadamard matrix, this
    new matrix must have the property $(H_{1}\otimes
    H_{2})(H_{1}\otimes H_{2})^{T}= n_{1}n_{2}I_{n_{1}n_{2}}$. Looking
    at $(H_{1}\otimes H_{2})(H_{1}\otimes H_{2})^{T}$ and using the
    above properties of Kronecker products, we get:
    \begin{align*}
      (H_{1}\otimes H_{2})(H_{1}\otimes H_{2})^{T} &= (H_{1}\otimes
      H_{2})(H_{1}^{T}\otimes H_{2}^{T})\\
      &= (H_{1}H_{1}^{T}\otimes H_{2}H_{2}^{T})\\
      &= n_{1} I_{n_{1}}\otimes n_{2}I_{n_{2}}= n_{1}n_{2}I_{n_{1}}I_{n_{2}}
    \end{align*}
    Thus, $H_{1}\otimes H_{2}$ is a Hadamard matrix.\cite{cameron1}
  \end{proof}
\end{theorem}
