Raymond E.\,A.\,C.\,Paley found a second construction for Hadamard
matrices in 1933.  His construction yields Hadamard matrices of the
size $q+1$, where $q=p^{r}\equiv 3\pmod{4}$.  In order to derive his
result, several definitions and theorems need to be given.  This
derivation of Paley’s result comes from Designs and Their Codes By
Assmus and Key\cite{assmus}. The proofs will be omitted
here, but they can be found in Designs and Their Codes.

Firstly, Paley’s theorem depends on quadratic residues of $\F_{4}$.
Quadratic residues are the elements $f\in\F_{4}$ that have a solution
$g\in\F_{4}$ to the equation $f=g^{2}$.

\begin{theorem}
  If $q=p^{r}$, where $p$ is an odd prime, then exactly half of the
  non-zero elements of $\F_{4}$ are squares.  Moreover, $-1$ is a
  square if and only if $q\equiv 1\pmod{4}$.
\end{theorem}
Next, it is necessary to define the Legendre symbol, which is a
character of the multiplicative group of $\F_{4}$.
\begin{definition}
   If $q$ is a power of an odd prime, then $c$, the Legendre symbol,
   defines the following mapping:
   \begin{align*}
     \chi&\colon\F_{4}\rightarrow (0,1,-1)\\
     \chi(x) &=
     \begin{cases}
       0 & x=0\\
       1 & x \text{is a non-zero}\\
       -1 & x \text{is a non-square}
     \end{cases}
   \end{align*}
\end{definition}
Using this mapping, it is possible to define a $q\times q$ matrix $Q=
(q_{ij})$, called the Jacobsthal matrix, whose row and column labels
are the elements of $\F_{4}$ and whose elements are $q=\chi (y-x)$.

Using the matrix $Q$ defined above,the following is Paley’s
construction:
\begin{theorem}
  If $q\equiv 3\pmod{4}$ and $Q$ is the Jacobsthal matrix for $\F_{4}$, then $H=
  \begin{pmatrix}
    1 & j\\
    j^{t} & Q
  \end{pmatrix}$
  is a Hadamard matrix of size q+1.\cite{assmus}
\end{theorem}
Paley also found two other existence theorems for Hadamard matrices
that appear in his 1933 paper.\cite{tressler}  They are as
follows:
\begin{theorem}
  Let $m$ be divisible by $4$ and of the form $2^{k} (p^{k}+1)$, where
  $p$ is an odd prime. Then we can construct a Hadamard matrix of
  order $m$.\cite{tressler}
\end{theorem}
\begin{theorem}
  Let $m$ be divisible by $4$ and of the form $2^{k}p(p^{k} +
  1)$,\todo{Ausdruck prüfen} where $q\equiv 3\pmod{4}$ is prime. Then
  we can construct a Hadamard matrix of order
  $m$.\cite{tressler}
\end{theorem}

When this result is combined with the Kronecker product, many Hadamard
matrices of orders previously unknown to exist can be found.  This
construction can find Hadamard matrices for all orders $n=4m$ up to $n
= 92$.\cite{tressler}

Williamson developed another construction for Hadamard matrices in
1944.  His construction is shown in the following theorem:
\begin{theorem}
  Suppose there exists $n\times n$ matrices $A$, $B$, $C$ and $D$ with
  the following properties:
  \begin{enumerate}
  \item $A$, $B$, $C$ and $D$ are symmetric matrices having entries $\pm1$.
  \item The matrices $A$, $B$, $C$ and $D$ commute.
  \item $A^{2}+B^{2}+C^{2}+D^{2}= 4nI_{n}$.
  \end{enumerate}
\end{theorem}
Then there exist a Hadamard matrix of order $4n$ given by:
\begin{gather*}
  H =
  \begin{pmatrix}
    A & B & C & D\\
    -B & A & D & -C\\
    -C & -D & A & B\\
    -D & C & -B & A
  \end{pmatrix}
\end{gather*}
This construction was used to find a Hadamard matrix of order 92,
which up until 1944 was the smallest factor of four without a known
Hadamard matrix.\cite{tressler}

\section{Codes Utilizing Hadamard Matrices}
\label{sec:codehm}

Coding theory is inspirited by the need to reliably transmit
information across a noisy channel.  In general, a code is simply a
collection of codewords to whom some meaning has been assigned.  Often
in coding, one is looking for a set of codewords that are dissimilar
or, in other words, have a large Hamming distance from one another.
The Hamming distance of two codewords is the number of places in which
the two words differ. The larger the Hamming distance, the easier it
is to detect and correct errors in a message, especially if the code
contains several errors.

Looking at the rows of a Hadamard matrix, it is evident that the
Hamming distance between any two rows is $\sfrac{n}{2}$.  This is true
since the rows are orthogonal to each other. This implies that half
the pairs must have a product of one (meaning the elements multiplied
were either $1$ and $1$ or $-1$ and $-1$) and half the pairs must have
a product of $-1$ (meaning one member of the pair was $-1$ and the
other $1$).  Thus, half of the entries of any one row are different
from the entries of any other row and the Hamming distance between the
rows is always $\sfrac{n}{2}$.  Therefore, as many as $\sfrac{n}{2}-1$
errors can be made in the transmission of a codeword and that codeword
can still be translated correctly.

Within coding, binary codes are often desirable. Any Hadamard matrix
can be turned into a binary matrix by changing all $-1$ into zeros.  By
doing so, the codewords become binary and the hamming distance between
words is preserved.

A Hadamard code is a code developed by taking each row a Hadamard
matrix as a codeword.  It is also possible to develop a shortened
Hadamard code.  To do so, one must first normalize a Hadamard matrix
so that the first column is made entirely of ones.  Then each codeword
can drop the leading one, thus constructing a code of length $n-1$ and
still having hamming distance
$\sfrac{n}{2}$.\cite{hallj}

Another class of codes that is closely related to Hadamard matrices
are the Reed-Muller codes.  I.\,S.\,Reed and D.\,E.\,Muller developed
these codes independently of one another in 1954.  This is a class of
binary codes of length $2^{m}$, for any positive integer $m$.  More
specifically, the Reed-Muller code $RM(1,m)^{\pm}$ is associated with
the Hadamard matrices of the Sylvester type.\cite{hallj}

Another desirable property of Hadamard codes and Reed-Muller codes is
the ability to decode the musing the Fast Hadamard transform.  This
decoding algorithm allows codes to be transformed much more
efficiently than they otherwise would have been.  For example, the
Reed-Muller code $RM(1,3)^{\pm}$ can be achieved in thirty-one steps,
rather than by as many as sixty-three steps using other
algorithms.\cite{hallj}

\section{Designs from Hadamard Matrices}
\label{sec:designs}

Designs are an important area for many reasons, most importantly in
statistics and design of experiments.  A $t-(v,k,\lambda)$ design is a
pair $(X,B)$ where $X$ is a set of $v$ points and $B$ is a collection
of $k$-subsets of $X$, called blocks, with the property that any $t$
points are contained in exactly $\lambda$ blocks.  In order to have a
non-trivial design the following conditions must occur: $t<k<v$ and
$\lambda>0$.\cite{cameron1}

Scientists need to know whether a design with certain parameters
actually exists.  Therefore, it is important to have constrictions for
designs if such a design is needed.  One example of a class of designs
are the Hadamard designs. It is possible to construct a Hadamard
design given a Hadamard matrix.  For this reason, the existence of
Hadamard matrices for all orders $n = 4m$ becomes even more important
since the existence of a Hadamard matrix implies the existence of a
design as well.  The following theorem details the connection between
Hadamard matrices and their designs.

\begin{theorem}\label{theo:10}
  For $n>4$, the following are equivalent:
  \begin{enumerate}
  \item There exists a Hadamard matrix of order $n$.
  \item There exists a $3- (n,\sfrac{1}{2}n, \sfrac{1}{4}n-1)$ design.
  \item There exists a $2- (n-1, \sfrac{1}{2}n-1, \sfrac{1}{4}n-1)$ design.\cite{cameron1}
  \end{enumerate}
\end{theorem}
Before proving this theorem, it is necessary to prove the following
theorem:
\begin{theorem}\label{theo:11}
  If $H$ is an Hadamard matrix with $m > 1$, then $n$ is even and for
  any two distinct rows of $H$ there are precisely $\sfrac{n}{2}$
  columns in which the entries of the two rows agree.  Further, if $n
  > 2$, then $n$ is divisible by $4$ and for any three distinct rows
  of $H$ there are precisely $\sfrac{n}{4}$ columns in which the
  entries in all three rows agree.  The same statements hold for the
  columns of $H$.\cite{assmus}
  \begin{proof}
    The first statement of \autoref{theo:11} is true because the rows
    are orthogonal. The argument for proving this statement is
    synonymous with the argument used to show the Hamming distance
    between the rows is $\sfrac{n}{2}$.  For the second part of the
    theorem, the proof comes from Designs and Their Codes by Assmus and
    Key.\cite{assmus} Suppose $n >2$.  Then $n$ is divisible
    by four and could be written as $n = 2r$.  Therefore, any two rows
    of $H$ agree in exactly $r$ places.  Let $x$, $y$ and $z$ be three
    distinct rows of $H$.  Let $A$ be the set of columns in which rows
    $x$ and $y$ agree and $D$ be the set of columns in which $x$ and
    $y$ differ.  The size of both $A$ and $D$ must be $r$.  Now
    looking at row $z$, let $A'$ be the columns in $A$ in which $z$
    and $x$ agree and let $D'$ be the columns in $D$ in which $x$ and
    $z$ agree. Thus the total number of places $x$ and $z$ agree is
    $A'+D'$ and, as a result, $A' + D' = r$.  Now looking at row $y$,
    the columns in $A$ in which $y$ and $z$ agree is also $A'$ and the
    columns in $D$ in which $y$ and $z$ agree are the compliment of
    those in $D’$. Therefore, the number of columns in which $y$ and
    $z$ agree is $A' + D-D'$, which also must equal $r$.

    Thus, one could set $A' + D'= A' + D -D'$ and solve to get $D'=
    \sfrac{r}{2}$ and, substituting this back into $A' + D'= r$, one
    would get $A' = \sfrac{r}{2}$.  Since the columns in $A'$ are the
    only columns in which all three rows agree, then the total number
    of places any set of three columns agree is $\sfrac{m}{4}$.  This
    theorem is true for the columns of a Hadamard matrix since the
    transpose of a Hadamard matrix is also a Hadamard
    matrix.\cite{assmus}
  \end{proof}
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  Using this information, it is possible to prove \autoref{theo:10}.
  The following is a proof from Combinatorics: Topics, Techniques,
  Algorithms by Cameron\cite{cameron1}. First, it is necessary
  to prove (i) implies (ii). Let $H= (h_{ij})$ be a Hadamard matrix of
  order $n$.  Normalize the matrix so that the entire first row is
  made of ones. For each row after the first, let $B_{i}^{+}= \Set{j |
    h_{ij}=+1}$ and let $B_{i}^{-}= \Set{j | h_{ij}=-1}$.  Also, let
  $X=\Set{1,2,\dots,n}$ and $B= \Set{B_{i}^{+}, B_{i}^{-} |
    i=2,3,\dots,n}$.  By \autoref{theo:11}, every row must match every
  other row in half the columns and differ in the other half of the
  columns.  Since the first row is made entirely of ones, then every
  other row must contain $\sfrac{n}{2}$ ones and $\sfrac{n}{2}$
  negative ones.  Thus, each block contains $\sfrac{n}{2}$ points as
  desired.  Also by \autoref{theo:11}, any three rows match in exactly
  $\sfrac{n}{4}$ columns.  Similarly, any three columns must match in
  exactly $\sfrac{n}{4}$ rows.  Since all the columns match in the
  first row, which was not used to create blocks, then each set of
  three columns meet on exactly $\sfrac{n}{4}-1$ of the sets in $B$.
  Thus, $(X,B)$ is a $3 - (n, \sfrac{1}{2}n, \sfrac{1}{4}n - 1)$
  design.

  Now, to show (ii) implies (iii), one can take the derived design
  with respect to one point, meaning that one point $p$ is deleted
  from all blocks and any blocks not incident to that point are also
  deleted. The result is a $2- (n-1, \sfrac{1}{2}n –1, \sfrac{1}{4}n –
  1)$ design.

  Now, in order to finish the proof of \autoref{theo:10}, (iii) must
  imply (i).  Suppose there exist a $2- (n-1, \sfrac{1}{2}n-1,
  \sfrac{1}{4}n- 1)$ design called $D$. Let $A$ be the incidence
  matrix of $D$.  First, replace all the zero entries of $A$ with
  negative ones and then border $A$ with a row and column of ones.
  The resulting matrix will be called $H$.  In $A$, any row had
  $\sfrac{n}{2}-1$ ones.  Thus, any row of $H$ after the first row of
  ones agrees with first row in exactly $\sfrac{n}{2}$ columns.  Now
  looking at any two rows of $A$, these rows both have ones in
  $\sfrac{n}{4}-1$ places and they both have zeros in $\sfrac{n}{4}$
  places.  This is a result of the complement of $D$ being a $2- (n-1,
  \sfrac{1}{2} n, \sfrac{1}{4}n)$ design.  Therefore, the
  corresponding rows in $H$ agree in exactly $\sfrac{n}{2}$ places.
  Therefore, any two rows on $H$ agree in exactly $\sfrac{n}{2}$
  places.  As a result, $H$ is a Hadamard
  matrix.\cite{cameron1}
\end{proof}

\section{Other Applications of Hadamard Matrices}
\label{sec:other}

Several other uses of Hadamard matrices exist besides those in coding
theory and the creation of designs.  One such use is in the creation
of weighing plans.  Weighing plans are used in experiments where the
measure of a set of objects is represented as the sum of the measures
of each object in the set. This is useful because, by weighing a group
of objects, one can more accurately determine the individual
measurements since any error in measurement will be spread across more
objects.\cite{agaian} Hadamard matrices can also be used in graph theory to
construct strongly regular graphs as well as tournaments.\cite{agaian} Also,
some Hadamard matrices are equivalent to Walsh functions, which are
important in many engineering applications.\cite{wallis} Overall, Hadamard
matrices can be an extremely useful tool to both scientists and
mathematicians. There is still much left to be discovered, however,
about this class of matrices.

